I'm SO looking forward to tonight. Phil and I are going out to watch 'One Man Star Wars'&nbsp; and then going for dinner at this amazing tiny little Greek/Turkish cafe. They make the best falafels in London and the best part is that it's pure indulgence but freshly made, no bits added to it, it's not oily, and I can just die happy eating there.&nbsp;

So I saved 18 points for dinner tonight! I can't wait. the thought of all those lovely salads, hummous (I shall learn to spell that word one day&nbsp;I swear), olives, peppers.... *drools*&nbsp;

Is it dinner time yet?

Today I actually told a colleague off for being disparinging about me losing weight. I commented on the fact that last Xmas I put on 9 pounds in 3 days and I was determined not to gain this Christmas by planning ahead. He said "that's what you think."&nbsp;

So I said "It's not helpful to me when you make comments like that, I am planning ahead and will succeed. If you don't have anything positive to say I would prefer it that you not say anything to me at all."

He shut up and changed the subject.&nbsp;

But it got me thinking on how many times that does actually happen? You say "oh I'm really doing well and going to succeed at this" and then someone feels the need to come along and piss on your parade? It's a hell of a lot more than you think and it just seriously annoys me.&nbsp;

I'll add more to this later but I'm at work and got to go to a meeting.

Been reading Paul McKenna's book - I can make you thin. Now I'm not usually into the self-help type books but it's a small book and I thought, what the hell. His rules though really stuck in my mind, particularly for someone like me who can just eat and eat and eat without any thought, and can also then not eat for an entire day because I don't feel like it.&nbsp;

In the book he said something that really stuck in my mind. Most over-weight people think about food a lot. They fantasize about it, plan what they're going to eat. And yet... very few actually enjoy or remember what they just ate.&nbsp;It really struck a chord because I know there have been times when it's not what I'm eating but the physical act of eating that's been key. I know I ate the pie, I just don't really remember&nbsp;eating the pie. The flavours, the textures, savouring it. I inhaled it and my tummy was stuffed and I wanted another one.&nbsp;

1. When hungry - EAT
2. Eat what you want to eat, don't force yourself to eat
3. ENJOY your food. Don't watch telly or read, concentrate on what you are eating (aka realise you're eating, not woolfing it down)
4. When you begin to feel full, STOP.&nbsp;

The difference between emotional hunger and real hunger is almost impossible to tell. But emotional hunger is swift and sudden, real hunger builds slowly. I definitely&nbsp;need to&nbsp;work on the emotional eating.&nbsp;

Reasons why I emotional eat:
- boredom
- upset
- tired
- avoidance (why clean when I can eat biscuits)

One of the weirder things I have noticed about myself is that I panic when food is taken away from me. Ok that sounds really weird. Let me explain - I become anxious in the following situations:
1. There is food left over and it's going to be thrown away. I feel I must eat it rather than waste. I have been known to literally force food into my mouth to avoid it being thrown away. 
2. Someone gets more on their plate than me.&nbsp;
Basically food deprivation makes me really anxious. Logically I know that there is food, but emotionally I'm "oh my god! I'm going to starve!". Also, thinking about it, I've equated food with satisfaction and calm for so long, that i see food being thrown away as almost like part of my happy is being thrown away. I know, I know. I'm writing this and thinking the same - this chick is nuts. But here's the thing. I'm not. Ask any truly overweight person how they feel about food and the honest truth is that it's a love affair - with it's up and downs, dirty secrets, cheating, tears, laughter, smiles, more tears.&nbsp;

So my task for the next two weeks is:
- eat when I am hungry, stop when I am full
- leave something on my plate every single meal, even if it's a pea or a carrot. No clean plates
- Any time I start to panic about food I&nbsp;ask repeat to myself&nbsp; "why is it important? Why am I anxious? Food to live, not live for food"

So I recently came back from a trip to LA. I would have posted earlier but I got home at 9pm on the Tuesday night and was at work at 8am on Wednesday morning. I also had to work this weekend so combined with jet lag you can just imagine. I'm not 100% back on a normal schedule yet, but getting there.&nbsp;

I'm really pleased that I lose weight while I was away. I decided not to track when I got there as it just proved a little too much to try and maintain. Instead I decided to just keep an eye on what I ate and make healthy choices, and to be honest be a little strict with myself.&nbsp;

I decided before I got there that I would not deprive myself, but would only eat burger, fries and pizza once, and only if we actually were somewhere where that was pretty much all the offered. So I did have all those things, but only once&nbsp;- when we went to a diner, so I had a burger, and when we went to a great little pizza parlour in Santa&nbsp;Monica, where I had a salad and a slice of pizza.&nbsp;

I mostly had salads and avoided cheese on things. Also - NO junk food snacks. Didn't buy crisps/chips at all. I did have some at a party we went too, but I'd had 4 tequlia shots by then so can happily forgive myself!

I think the worst part was actually coming back to the UK and being swamped by work. I sort of feel that I allowed too much free reigh coming home in terms of food and have had takeaways twice, and been eating sandwiches from the canteen. So weigh-in was last night, and as of today I am firmly back on tracking. Not very well as I had a business lunch, but tonight I'm having a nice salad to balance that out. Also shopping tonight to get back in line with correct food in the fridge and planning dinner tomorrow night for me and my boyfriend Phil.&nbsp;

So yeah, it was pretty good and I'm quite chuffed with myself!

When I started this LJ I was rather - it'll all about weight. Well I think I'll drive myself nuts before I drive anyone else nuts with weight, weight, weight talk.&nbsp;

So...&nbsp;

Right now I am tired because...

my housemate played weird German yodel-wailing music until 1am this morning. And this morning turned the tap on in the kitchen while I was showering.&nbsp;

I was&nbsp;not impressed.&nbsp;

I live with two other woman, I'm the youngest at 29 (30 in a few months) and sometimes the tension is a little fraught. We all cook seperately, we're all so busy there is no way we could cook together. Last night's dinner consisted of 2 slices of bacon and a boiled egg simply because I couldn't be bothered to clean the sink clear of all the washing up that was in there, or drying. I just dumped my frying pan on top.&nbsp;

Ah the joys of house sharing.

I've been thinking about the purpose of this LJ. I created it with the intent of making it just about me and my weight, but I do realise that may be incredibley boring to not only myself but anyone who comes and reads it (if anyone other than my boyfriend, hi honey!). Thing is though, I do have another LJ where I rant and scream at the world and I am loathe to mix the two. Juicyfruit is me just being me, nothing added. And I think I like it that way. So I'm going to stick to this format for a while and see how it goes. But I can talk about food a lot :) 

Edit - just been watching the news about the closing of airports etc due to terror alerts. *sigh* I'm off to US at the beginning of Sep and fly back on, wait for it... 11 Sep. Oh yes. I couldn't have picked it better. My main worry is not the 10 hours of getting through security, but whether or not I'll fit into the&nbsp;airplane seat&nbsp;on the way back after spending 10 days eating out in the US. The last time I was there I ordered a burger at Friday's that when it arrived it&nbsp; was bigger than my head and the pickle on the side was longer than my arm. And the sad thing? I really could've eaten the whole thing. I didn't cause even then, when I was happily piling on the weight, I knew that eating 1/2 a cow wasn't the best idea in the world.&nbsp; 

Oh god. Oreo cookie milkshakes. *staples mouth shut*
